<description>
<section>
<title>Experimental Design</title>
<para>4 productivity gradients. Each gradient is composed of 3 sites (high, medium, and low aboveground production). Each site is composed of 3 plots. Each plot is 20m x 20m.

4 sites were selected from the Growth and Yield program (E.C.Packee).</para>
</section>
<section>
<title>Methods</title>
<para>Soil description and sampling:
Twelve soil pits (approximately 0.25 m2, to a depth of 5 cm mineral soil) were dug at each site to accurately describe horizon and char-layer depths, and to collect soil charcoal samples (for 14C dating). Three soil cores (5.08 cm diameter) were obtained near the best face at each soil pit. Genetic horizons were separated in the field and bulked at each pit. Mineral soils have been dried, sieved, and analyzed for bulk density and C and N content. Subsamples have been taken for incubation experiments this winter. Organic horizon samples will similarly be analyzed this winter.
Data collection and preparation:
Stand level information (tree diameters, stand density, and tree heights) has been collected at each site. Six litter traps (0.25 m2) were randomly distributed at every site except those in the Kenai peninsula by mid July. Litter was collected in Oct. for d13C quantification this winter. Litter inputs to the soil will be measured for the next two years. Root-exclusion (mini-trench) ollars were inserted 30 cm into the soil at 10 random points within each high- and low-productivity site. These will be harvested in two years to assess the net effect of root inputs to soil carbon stocks. Soil and air temperatures (by genetic horizon and at 1 m above the soil surface, respectively) are being continuously monitored with portable data loggers (HOBO H8) installed at each site. Twelve cellulose decomposition assays (filter paper) have been installed in organic (6) and mineral (6) soils at each site. Harvests of Organic and mineral soil assays will occur in one and two years, respectively.</para>
</section>
